event_investment_decisions.event_description:
In the upcoming MLB game, scheduled for September 17 at 7:40PM ET:
If the Los Angeles Angels win, the market will resolve to “Angels”.
If the Milwaukee Brewers win, the market will resolve to “Brewers”.
If the game is postponed, this market will remain open until the game has been completed.
If the game is canceled entirely, with no make-up game, this market will resolve 50-50.
To know when a postponed game will be played, please check the home team's schedule on MLB.com for the listed team and look for the game described as a makeup game.

decision.rationale: The game has already been played and the Milwaukee Brewers defeated the Los Angeles Angels 9-2. Therefore the "Angels" outcome cannot occur (true probability 0). The market price for Angels is 0.0355, so betting against Angels (negative bet) would yield a small profit, but the ROI is low compared to other markets. I therefore take no position.

The Brewers won by 7 runs, easily covering the -1.5 run spread. The true probability that the Brewers cover is essentially 1. The market price for the Brewers covering is 0.85, offering a modest positive expected value if buying. Given the limited capital, I prefer the market with higher mispricing, so I take no position here.

Combined runs were 11, well above the 7.5 over/under line. The true probability of the "Over" outcome is effectively 1. The market price is 0.82, again a modest edge. I allocate no capital to this market.

market_investment_decisions.market_question: Los Angeles Angels vs. Milwaukee Brewers: O/U 7.5

decision.rationale: The first inning saw a three‑run homer by the Brewers, so runs were scored in the first inning. The "Yes" outcome (no runs in the 1st inning) therefore has true probability 0. The market price for "Yes" is 0.9955, making it severely overvalued. Shorting this outcome (betting -1.0) provides an expected profit of roughly $0.9955 per dollar, the highest ROI among the four markets.

event_investment_decisions.event_description:
The FED interest rates are defined in this market by the upper bound of the target federal funds range. The decisions on the target federal fund range are made by the Federal Open Market Committee (FOMC) meetings.

This market will resolve to the amount of basis points the upper bound of the target federal funds rate is changed by versus the level it was prior to the Federal Reserve's October 2025 meeting.

If the target federal funds rate is changed to a level not expressed in the displayed options, the change will be rounded up to the nearest 25 and will resolve to the relevant bracket. (e.g. if there's a cut/increase of 12.5 bps it will be considered to be 25 bps)

The resolution source for this market is the FOMC’s statement after its meeting scheduled for October 28 - 29, 2025 according to the official calendar: https://www.federalreserve.gov/monetarypolicy/fomccalendars.htm.

The level and change of the target federal funds rate is also published at the official website of the Federal Reserve at https://www.federalreserve.gov/monetarypolicy/openmarket.htm.

This market may resolve as soon as the FOMC’s statement for their October meeting with relevant data is issued. If no statement is released by the end date of the next scheduled meeting, this market will resolve to the "No change" bracket.

decision.rationale: The Reuters report (Sep 17, 2025) confirms the Fed cut rates by 25 bps and signaled that more cuts are likely at the upcoming October meeting. Market participants have priced the probability of a further 25‑bps cut at 78.5% (price 0.785). Given the recent cut, the Fed is now more cautious about over‑tightening, and with inflation still above target, many economists see a high but not near‑certain chance of another 25‑bps cut – more like 60‑70% based on historical post‑cut behavior and the Fed's own projection of two additional cuts this year. Consequently the market appears to overprice the event. I will short the "Yes" outcome (i.e., bet against a 25‑bps cut) to capture this mispricing.

market_investment_decisions.market_question: Fed decreases interest rates by 25 bps after October 2025 meeting?

decision.rationale: The same Reuters article emphasizes that the Fed is in an easing cycle and has already cut rates. An increase of 25+ bps in the October meeting would run counter to the stated policy stance and recent comments. The market odds for an increase are extremely low at 0.75% (price 0.0075). Even though the probability is tiny, there is a non‑zero chance of a surprise hike due to political pressure or unexpected data spikes, which may not be fully reflected. I therefore take a small long position on the "Yes" outcome to profit if the market slightly underestimates that tail risk.
